Accurate targeting of treatment sites should increase local control by radiation therapy for breast-cancer lumpectomy patients.

 Currently, ultrasound localization is used for prostate cancer patients to locate the prostate before daily radiation treatments.

 There is now documented evidence that the lumpectomy site does change during the external radiation therapy.

 Thus, treatment efficacy should be increased by localizing the target, monitoring volume changes, and adjusting the radiation target prior to the boost radiation dose.

